Date: Tue, 15 Feb 2000 12:06:58 +0000
From: Simon Parker <sparker@nibsc.ac.uk>

In relation to the 'ticks and tapeworms statement' previously mentioned...
I think if you substitute 'vaccination' with the more accurate phrase
'treated' you will get a more accurate rendition of the quarantine changes.
Before pets are allowed to enter or reenter the UK they must be treated
against the fox tapeworm (_Echinococcus multilocularis_) using praziquantel
and ticks (_Rhipicephalus sanguineus_) using an acaricide by a qualified
person in the county of origin. The document ..Memorandum on Rabies
Prevention and Control is available on the Department of Health Website at
<http://www.doh.gov.uk/memorandumonrabies/> and further information on the
Implementation of the Pet travel scheme, which will hopefully be applied to
other pets in 2001 is available on
<http://www.maff.gov.uk/animalh/quarantine/>
--
Simon Parker
e-mail: sparker@nibsc.ac.uk
