[2
Date: Tue, 15 Feb 2000 11:00:52 -0500 (EST)
From: James Allan <james_allan@sandwich.pfizer.com>

The reasoning behind the requirements for treatment of dogs for tapeworms
under the revised UK quarantine regulations is as follows:
_ Echinococcus multilocularis_, which is endemic in several continental
European countries including France, Switzerland, Austria and Germany, is
non endemic to the UK. This parasite which is extremely dangerous to humans
normally has a sylvatic life cycle (foxes harbor the adult, intestinal
stage and rodents harbor the larval stage) but both dogs and cats can
become infected with the intestinal tapeworm stage (by eating infected
rodents).
Humans can harbor the larval stage and become infected by ingestion of eggs
in the feces of the definitive host (foxes, dogs or cats). Humans develop
the larval stage of the parasite normally in the liver. The parasite in the
human is very difficult to treat (lobectomies and liver transplants are
used in several EU countries) and chemotherapy is difficult. It develops
relatively slowly in humans and it can take several years for symptoms to
show. There are several human cases of this disease every year in France,
Germany, Switzerland and Austria and, over the past 20 years or so, it has
in fact caused more fatalities than rabies in these countries. The tapeworm
treatment for pets (not vaccination) is designed to stop the parasite being
imported to the UK.
On a separate issue _E. granulosus_ is already endemic in the UK. There is,
for instance, a well documented focus in the Brecon area of Wales. The
treatment of pets is not therefore designed to keep this parasite out of
the UK as it is already there.
--
James Allan
e-mail: james_allan@sandwich.pfizer.com
